The machine is quite powerful and runs AAA titles upto 2018 effortlessly for normal usage. I don't stream or have massive external monitors, so can't say much about those scenarios... But if you're looking for a machine that does what it says by its own hardware, this is a simply a great investment. Also runs CAD/CNC software no problem.

One heads up: do NOT install the latest nvidia drivers from the Nvidia website.
Only download (if needed) the recommended Nvidia drivers from the MSI website.

For more info, the MSI website has a good FAQ for most of your questions so do check that out once.

And yes, you CAN upgrade the RAM and Hard drive/SSD WITHOUT voiding the warranty. The factory seal sticker on the bottom lid is only to tell you that it hasn't been opened before you got it.
This upgrade/warranty info is from MSI's website (Q.18 in their FAQ), and it still states that if you screw ANYTHING up while doing the upgrade (yourself), that damage will be on you and obviously NOT be covered under warranty. This is a no-brainer so don't go yelling to MSI about it, in case you botch the upgrade.

Cons :-
1st - Doesn't support HDMI output through NVidia GPU but only through Intel GPU, so can't play games on bigger screen
2nd - Thermals are pretty average, since MSI decided to show 2 fans in pic but in reality it only has 1 fan, Shame on you MSI for falls advertisement.
3rd - GPU is severely underperforming even for a 3050 thanks to it being limited to 40 Watt TDP, 3050 can have max TDP of 80 Watt and achieve much higher clock speed, 60-65 Watt power should have been fine with 2 fans and an AC-Adapter of 135/150 Watt instead of 120 Watt.
4th - 120 Watt AC adapter just isn’t enough, while gaming your battery will slowly drain cause AC-Adapter alone isn’t able to keep up with the power-draw.
5th - You can feel a soft ting of static-electricity while hard pressing a key on side, if your skin comes in contact with internal part of chassis while typing with AC-Adapter on, I would say anti-static paint job wasn't done well in key-holes on chassis.
6th - Don’t have access to HDD/RAM port without opening the whole case and voiding the warranty, if you want upgradability in future then only buy it you have an MSI certified service center nearby, but MSI have pretty bad coverage compared to other brands, they only good service for Delhi/Mumbai/Bengaluru etc.

Pros -
1st - 10500H is beast of a processor with 6 Cores/12 threads, performance is easily comparable to an i7, also don’t go for MSI GF63 Thin with i7-10750H/RTX 3050 cause that CPU is even more power hungry and would leave even less wattage for RTX 3050, thanks to MSI giving same 120 Watt AC adapter with that one as well, again shame on you MSI.

First of all thanks to Flipkart and MSI for providing such a machine at 59K during sale period.
Disclaimer:
I'm a professional editor and my review will based on productivity usage and not gaming.

Ive been using this laptop for about a month now, and during the period I've used it in many scenarios such as on location during shoot for basic data transferring and proxy creation to editing rough cuts while travelling in a train. And overall I love this laptop. For the price I bought it, I can't think of any other better option as of now.
Now let's get objective and present pros and cons of this machine:
1. It is light weight and thin for a gaming laptop. My 4 year Asus ROG weighed 2.8kgs and carrying that around was pain in the back. But this thin laptop at 1.8kgs feels like nothing.
2. The Hexa core I5 along with RTX 3050 give beautiful performance, frankly while editing 6k footage from Blackmagic cinema camera I didn't miss my main workstation. Davinci Resolve loves this laptop.
3. This laptop allows you to upgrade the RAM to 64gb, by next year I'll probably utilise it.
4. 144hz screen makes the day today task feel really smooth, I know it means alot for gaming but for me the smooth scrolling and dragging is just buttery.
5. Speakers are decently loud and clear, exceeded my expectation.
6. I love the fact that MSI didn't waste any ports on USB 2.0, all the USB ports support 5gbps.
7. Webcam quality is pretty good. In normal room light the footage is clean and microphone along with Nvidia broadcast app is simply excellent with AI based noise cancellation.
8. In Delhi, Service centre guys are super cooperative, I visited one near my house to get RAM and HDD upgraded, they did it smilingly. Try to visit HP or Lenovo for the same job, they'll give you thousands of excuses.
9. 2 years warranty makes the whole deal sweeter.

Now some cons:
1. While doing heavy duty tasks the keyboard area warms up alot. My old laptop didn't have this issue, physically it was pretty thick and allowed better cooling option. Maybe the thin form factor limits the heat dispersion via fans, MSI could improve it in the next iteration. Please Note that there's no dangerous overheating.
2. No 10 gbps usb port. It was very strange that MSI didn't include 10gbps port, it's 2021 and almost every gaming laptop above 50k has atleast one 10gbps port.
3. MSI should offer better display option as this screen is colour inaccurate. An option for 100%srgb or 90% DCI p3 would have made this laptop perfect for creators. I mean I'm still ready to pay an extra 5-6k for upgrading to a better display.
4. Laptop drivers are a bit unstable, there were times when I was just using Word and excel but for no reason discrete GPU ran in the background and battery went from 100 to 20 in 1.5hrs. On some good days I managed to watch Prime video for 5 straight hours on battery because internal gpu was active. MSI needs to fix this.

In all its a great machine for the price. Would recommend it even at 65k as it's powerful and light. Great job MSI.

Have you ever watched the movie 'Beauty and the beast'? Well this laptop by MSI is a beauty as well as a beast.
i5-10500H along with the rtx 3050 4gb graphics works as smooth as butter. (As the i5-1500H has 6cores and 12 threads there won't be any bottleneck issues). We get a 144hz refresh rate screen, that too with an anti-glare display with 45% NTSC color gamut. At this price it's more than enough. The webcam could have been improved a bit, but well a lot of gaming laptops are doing away with the webcam.
Coming to the battery backup, it gives you 5 modes through the dragon centre (gaming mode 2.0) and you can also customise it to your needs. The maximum single charge return that I got was 8 hours (super battery + battery saving mode), and it's fine with me, considering that this is a gaming laptop.
The dual speaker is decent and gives a good sound experience. You can again customize it according to your needs through the Nahimic software.
The built of the laptop is good, and the top lid as well as the keyboard (Steelseries keyboard) doesnt have a lot of flex issues. In fact its the bare minimum.
With this laptop one will get the latest Wi-Fi 6 and Bluetooth 5.1 l, so you will be sorted regarding the connectivity. Also remember, along with this laptop you will be getting a free Windows 11 update.
One will get a 1x Type-C USB3.2 Gen1 and 3x Type-A USB3.1 Gen1 ports, 1 RJ45 port as well as a HDMI port.
Also I got a 2 years warranty with this laptop so it's a Win-win. The ram can be expanded till 64 gb and we also get extra slot for a hdd.
So considering all this, the laptop is quite good at the price range and is suitable for gaming as well as productivity.

I bought this at 58K during BBD sale, and it justified the price.
In the said price range, it is very competetive and affordable machine. I'll list the areas which I feel could be improved later in the review.

1. 144HZ monitor - Awesome
2. It is very light
3. Build Quality is OK, does not feel cheap.
4. Thermals - As soon as CPU Temp reaches 80, it comes down automatically. Same is for gpu too, but the temperature threshold for GPU is above 80 degree Celsius. Heat will not be noticed while playing.
4. 3050 - despite being 40W, 4GB I played Hunt Showdown and Deadside both on highest setting and managed to get more than 60fps with refresh rate of monitor 144HZ. Everything is so smooth.

Now things that can be improved:
1. Brightness is less as compared to other laptops
2. GPU sometimes suffer when the CPU temperature reaches 80°. You may feel kind of lag for few milliseconds when the hardware brings down the temp of CPU, but this can be ignored
3. Trackpad tap is kind of ugly and clutter, use usb or wireless mouse
4. We have to visit service center in case anything goes wrong or if we wish to upgrade RAM/ SSD/HDD

Overall, for 58K this is the best bang for buck. Also, I missed to mention that both of the above games recorded on highest settings using OBS at 144HZ refresh rate at 60FPS if you are into game recording. I haven't yet checked the streaming but I think it will be smooth. Used for 2-3 days, performance is great, display is awesome, Ram is less but it's upgradeable, CPU and GPU are perfectly matched in performance so they don't bottleneck each other, battery life is good for a gaming laptop although I wouldn't recommend gaming on battery.
Factory seal is big down point because without breaking that one cannot perform any upgrades. This is a very negative point for msi as it's known for gaming laptops so they should be easily upgradable.

All in all a good, value for money, entry level gaming laptop

Design and Build:
Excellent build. Slim profile for a gaming laptop. Keyboard is very nice with only Red Backlighting. Trackpad is bit small but that's okay for a gaming laptop.

Display and Speakers:
Smooth 144Hz display for competitive e-sports titles. Don't expect color accuracy here. It purely meant for content consumption and not creation.
Speakers are really crisp with decent bass. Webcam is poor but does the job.

Battery:
Battery is okay. One thing to note, if your battery drops below 100% and you immediately connect the charger, the battery won't charge. You have to discharge the battery below 80% then only charging will happen.

Performance and Upgrade:
Performance for the price is top notch. Don't listen to people saying it has only Rtx3050 with low TDP and go with numbers. Leave those people aside. You will have no problems in gaming. Tried Warzone, Fortnite, The Division 1 & 2, RDR2. Everything plays perfectly. Use a cooling pad while gaming as it heats near the WASD keys. Basic code compilation and designing apps work flawlessly.
There is a free 2.5 inch HDD/SSD slot and RAM can be expanded to upto 64GB. But you will LOSE WARRANTY! Since you have to break the warranty sticker to perform upgrade.

ALSO DON'T LISTEN TO THE PEOPLE SAYING BAD THINGS ABOUT THE CPU OR GPU! THIS IS A REALLY GREAT LAPTOP FOR THE PRICE.

Performance: Does play most current AAA titles with minimal gitter.
Note: The gpu is set to use 40w max, I might overclock it later. Also another 8gb dual channel RAM would be great.

Screen: Fast screen with 144hz refresh rate, Good for gaming.
Don't expect picture quality as of a retina display. Anti glare is not that great, so outdoor use might be a bit troubling.

Battery: Decent enough, its a gaming laptop don't expect much in the first place. I love the fact that it comes with Dragon center pre-installed. It has options to select optimum settings for overall PC performance and hardware health.

Overall if you're looking for a mid ranger laptop for indoor Gaming it the best at the price(around 62k).
